#week-title("Three", "Observing Without Opening: Advanced Perceptual Practice")

=== Core Teaching

The observation discipline established in Year Two Month 9 for the long
circulation is now extended and deepened for the mineral preparations. The
mineral work demands a higher degree of perceptual sensitivity than the
vegetable work because:

- Changes in mineral preparations are slower and more subtle than in vegetable
  preparations — the difference between a preparation at month two and month
  four of a slow digestion may be barely visible to an untrained eye.
- The sealed mineral vessel cannot be opened for inspection — only light and
  colour changes visible through the glass serve as indicators.
- The signs of the Peacock's Tail and subsequent colour stages require the
  practitioner to have developed a fine enough perceptual memory to notice
  changes that occur over days and weeks, not hours.

*Advanced perceptual practices for mineral observation:*

- *Photographing under consistent conditions:* same light source, same angle,
  same distance, same time of day — so that photographs across weeks and months
  are genuinely comparable. Even a slight change in lighting can make a yellow
  preparation look green or a grey preparation look white.
- *The translucency test:* hold the flask against a consistent light source
  (a white LED lamp or north-facing window on a bright day). Observe how light
  passes through the preparation. A preparation that was opaque and is now
  partially translucent has undergone a genuine change in its internal structure.
- *Colour matching:* keep a reference colour chart (even a simple painted swatch
  in the long-work log) against which the preparation's colour is compared at
  each observation. Words like "grey-brown" mean different things to different
  observers on different days; a colour swatch anchors the description.
- *The smell test without opening:* If the vessel has any porosity in its seal
  (even a tiny gap), the preparation's progress is sometimes detectable by scent
  — a changing smell at the vessel's joint can indicate a change in the
  preparation's volatile character. (This is also a leak diagnostic — if you
  can smell the preparation, address the seal immediately.)

=== Topics This Week

- Advanced observation protocols for sealed mineral preparations
- Consistent photography as a memory aid for slow colour changes
- The translucency test: light transmission as a diagnostic
- Colour matching and reference charts in the long-work log

#inner-work[
  *Sustained Attention at the Mineral Level*

  Sit with one of your sealed mineral preparations for twenty minutes using
  the full observation protocol: consistent lighting, reference to your colour
  chart, translucency test.

  Record what you observe with maximum precision. Then record: what does it
  require of you to sustain this level of attention to something so apparently
  static? What has changed in your capacity for this kind of attention since
  Year One?
]

